  "prompt": "What records are unlikely to be broken, ever?",
  "response": "Some sports records are considered so extraordinary that many experts believe they are unlikely to be broken, ever. Here are a few examples:\n\n1. **Wilt Chamberlain's 100-Point Game (1962)**  \n   - Wilt Chamberlain scored 100 points in a single NBA game, a feat that remains unparalleled and is widely considered unbreakable due to changes in the game's style and pace.\n\n2. **Cal Ripken Jr.'s Iron Man Streak (2,632 Consecutive Games)**  \n   - Cal Ripken Jr. played 2,632 consecutive MLB games over 16 years, a testament to durability and consistency that seems impossible to surpass in the modern era of sports science and player management.\n\n3. **Usain Bolt's 100m and 200m World Records (9.58s and 19.19s)**  \n   - Bolt's sprinting records are often regarded as untouchable due to the combination of his physical gifts and the near-perfect execution of his races.\n\n4. **Wayne Gretzky's Career Points (2,857)**  \n   - Gretzky's NHL record for total points (goals + assists) is so far ahead of anyone else that it\u2019s often referred to as untouchable, even by modern hockey standards.\n\n5. **Jahangir Khan's 555-Match Winning Streak in Squash**  \n   - Jahangir Khan won 555 consecutive matches from 1981 to 1986, a dominance in an individual sport that seems impossible to replicate.\n\n6. **Katie Ledecky's 1500m Freestyle World Record (15:20.48)**  \n   - Ledecky\u2019s time in the women\u2019s 1500m freestyle is so far ahead of her peers that it\u2019s considered one of the most unbreakable records in swimming.\n\n7. **Edwin Moses' 122-Consecutive Wins in the 400m Hurdles**  \n   - Moses dominated the 400m hurdles for nearly a decade, winning 122 consecutive races, a streak that seems unattainable in modern athletics.\n\n8. **High Jump (Javier Sotomayor - 2.45m), Pole Vault (Sergey Bubka - 6.14m)**  \n   These field event records have stood for decades and are considered near the physical limits of human capability.\n\nThese records often stand out due to the unique combination of talent, timing, and circumstances that made them possible, and they continue to be benchmarks of human achievement in sports.",
